type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

! TiddlyWiki Resizer Widget Plugin

A flexible, pointer-based resizer widget for TiddlyWiki. It can resize one tiddler, multiple tiddlers, live DOM elements, paired split panes, real HTML table columns, and CSS Grid column/row tracks. It supports horizontal and vertical resizing, CSS units, `calc()` expressions, min/max constraints, optional snap points, double-click preset cycling, CSS variable publishing, pointer/touch input, haptic feedback, double-click reset, action hooks, a dedicated `split-pair` mode for adjacent panels, a `table-column` mode for real HTML tables, and a `grid-track` mode for CSS Grid table-like layouts with overlay handles, ghost cells, placed cell tiddlers, per-cell padding defaults, configurable block/inline cell rendering, adaptive filler tracks (`fillLastColumn` / `fillLastRow`), explicit positional track defaults (`colDefaults` / `rowDefaults`), and CSS-level column minimums (`colMinWidth`).

The widget is intended for TiddlyWiki layouts where sizes are stored in state/config tiddlers and reused as CSS values. Normal `single` and `multiple` modes resize target values directly. The `split-pair` mode treats two adjacent panes as one coupled pair: the first pane grows by the drag delta, the second pane shrinks by the same amount, and the pair's total size stays stable. The `table-column` mode resizes the real `<col>` element of an HTML table instead of trying to resize each `<td>` cell individually. The `grid-track` mode resizes the boundary between two adjacent CSS Grid tracks. In column mode it resizes the boundary between two columns; in row mode it resizes the boundary between two rows. This is the right model for resizable CSS Grid tables with merged cells, ghost cells, overlay handles, tiddler-driven placement, and optional full-height row resizing.

The refactored plugin keeps the public widget entry point compatible with the original monolithic widget while moving internal behavior into focused modules. Existing usage should continue to work, and the newer features are additive and opt-in.

