!! Single-Target Resizing

Single-target resizing writes one value into one tiddler field.

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/panel/width"
  field="text"
  unit="px"
  min="200px"
  max="800px"
  default="350px"
/>
```

Use the value:

```html
<div class="panel" style.width={{$:/state/panel/width}}>
  Panel
</div>
```

Vertical example:

```html
<$resizer
  direction="vertical"
  tiddler="$:/state/header/height"
  field="text"
  unit="px"
  min="48px"
  max="240px"
  default="96px"
/>
```

For flexbox, prefer:

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/sidebar/width"
  selector=".sidebar"
  property="flexBasis"
  live="yes"
/>
```

!! Multiple-Target Resizing

Use `filter` to resize several tiddlers at once.

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  filter="$:/metrics/storyright $:/metrics/storywidth $:/metrics/tiddlerwidth"
  unit="px"
  min="300px"
  max="calc(100vw - 350px)"
/>
```

You can also use a normal TiddlyWiki filter expression:

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  filter="[tag[layout-metric]]"
  unit="px"
  min="100px"
  max="800px"
/>
```

In multiple mode, each target's original unit is detected and preserved where possible. Internally, each value is converted to pixels, constrained, and then converted back.

!! Split-Pair Resizing

`split-pair` mode is for adjacent split panes. It is the recommended mode for resizable columns and stacked panes.

!!! How split-pair works

At drag start, the widget measures:

```text
parent size
primary pane size
secondary pane size
pair size = primary + secondary
```

During drag:

```text
primary = primaryStart + delta
secondary = pairStart - primary
```

So the pair stays stable while the divider moves.

!!! Horizontal split pair

```html
<div class="split split-horizontal">
  <div class="pane" style.width={{$:/state/split/left}}>Left</div>
  <$resizer
    class="splitter splitter-vertical"
    direction="horizontal"
    mode="split-pair"
    unit="%"
    element="previousSibling"
    leftTiddler="$:/state/split/left"
    rightTiddler="$:/state/split/right"
    leftField="text"
    rightField="text"
    min="15%"
    splitPairLiveResize="yes"
    splitPairSave="end"
  />
  <div class="pane" style.width={{$:/state/split/right}}>Right</div>
</div>
```

!!! Horizontal split pair with CSS variables

```html
<div class="split split-horizontal btc-split">
  <div class="pane left-pane">Left</div>
  <$resizer
    class="splitter splitter-vertical"
    direction="horizontal"
    mode="split-pair"
    unit="%"
    element="previousSibling"
    leftTiddler="$:/state/split/left"
    rightTiddler="$:/state/split/right"
    leftCssVariable="--btc-left-width"
    rightCssVariable="--btc-right-width"
    cssVariableTarget="root"
    min="15%"
    splitPairLiveResize="yes"
    splitPairSave="end"
  />
  <div class="pane right-pane">Right</div>
</div>
```

```css
.left-pane {
  flex: 0 0 var(--btc-left-width, 50%);
}

.right-pane {
  flex: 0 0 var(--btc-right-width, 50%);
}
```

!!! Vertical split pair

```html
<div class="split split-vertical">
  <div class="pane" style.height={{$:/state/split/top}}>Top</div>
  <$resizer
    class="splitter splitter-horizontal"
    direction="vertical"
    mode="split-pair"
    unit="%"
    element="previousSibling"
    topTiddler="$:/state/split/top"
    bottomTiddler="$:/state/split/bottom"
    topField="text"
    bottomField="text"
    min="15%"
    splitPairLiveResize="yes"
    splitPairSave="end"
  />
  <div class="pane" style.height={{$:/state/split/bottom}}>Bottom</div>
</div>
```

!!! Resizer inside the first pane

If the resizer is rendered inside the left/top pane, use:

```html
element="parent"
```

Example for dynamic TiddlyWiki columns:

```html
<$resizer
  class="tc-flexbox-story-column-resizer-flexbox"
  direction="horizontal"
  mode="split-pair"
  min="15%"
  default=<<cellWidth>>
  unit="%"
  element="parent"
  leftTiddler={{{ [<stateTiddlerPrefix>addsuffix<colIndex>] }}}
  rightTiddler={{{ [<stateTiddlerPrefix>addsuffix<nextColIndex>] }}}
  leftField="text"
  rightField="text"
  splitPairLiveResize="yes"
  splitPairSave="end"
/>
```

For this pattern, the target element must be the left/top pane itself. The widget then finds the right/bottom pane with `targetElement.nextElementSibling`.

!!! CSS for stable split-pair layouts

For horizontal flex columns:

```css
.split-horizontal {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  width: 100%;
  min-width: 0;
}

.split-horizontal > .pane {
  flex-grow: 0;
  flex-shrink: 0;
  min-width: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```

For vertical flex panes:

```css
.split-vertical {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  height: 100%;
  min-height: 0;
}

.split-vertical > .pane {
  flex-grow: 0;
  flex-shrink: 0;
  min-height: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```

`splitPairLiveResize="yes"` updates the DOM styles and `flex-basis` during drag. Combine it with `splitPairSave="end"` so the widget saves the final tiddler values only once on pointer release. This avoids repeated TiddlyWiki refreshes while dragging and gives the smoothest split-pair resizing.

!!! When not to use split-pair

Do not use `split-pair` if you only want to change one stored value. Use normal `single` mode instead.

Do not also run Wikitext `onResize` actions that rewrite the same pair tiddlers unless you intentionally want custom override logic. Otherwise you will have two systems writing sizes at once.

!! Table-Column Resizing

`mode="table-column"` resizes an HTML table column by creating or reusing a `<colgroup>` and changing the width of the correct `<col>`.

This is the correct model for real table resizing. Do not resize every `<td>` in a column individually. Cells are table contents; the column model belongs in `<colgroup>`.

!!! Basic table-column example

```html
<table class="my-table" data-resizer-id="issues">
  <tr>
    <th>Issue</th>
    <th>Status</th>
    <th>Notes</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>#1</td>
    <td>Open</td>
    <td>Long note text</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  mode="table-column"
  tableSelector=".my-table"
  tableColumnIndex="2"
  unit="px"
  min="80px"
  max="500px"
  tableColumnLiveResize="yes"
  tableColumnSave="end"
/>
```

!!! Column index detection

If `tableColumnIndex` is omitted, the widget tries to infer the column index from the clicked `td` or `th`.

This is useful when the resizer handle is rendered inside a cell:

```html
<th>
  Notes
  <$resizer
    mode="table-column"
    direction="horizontal"
    unit="px"
    min="80px"
    max="500px"
    tableColumnLiveResize="yes"
  />
</th>
```

!!! Stable table ids

Use `tableColumnId` or `data-resizer-id` for stable state tiddler names:

```html
<table class="my-table" data-resizer-id="project-table">
```

or:

```html
<$resizer
  mode="table-column"
  tableSelector=".my-table"
  tableColumnId="project-table"
/>
```

Without a stable id, class names can become part of the generated tiddler title. That works, but it is less predictable.

!!! Recommended table CSS

```css
.my-table {
  table-layout: fixed;
  width: 100%;
}

.my-table th,
.my-table td {
  overflow: hidden;
  text-overflow: ellipsis;
}
```

The widget also sets `table.style.tableLayout = "fixed"` during live column resizing if no table layout is already set.

!!! Save behavior

Use `tableColumnSave="drag"` if you want the state tiddler updated continuously.

Use `tableColumnSave="end"` if you want a smoother drag with one final write on pointerup.

```html
<$resizer
  mode="table-column"
  tableColumnSave="end"
  tableColumnLiveResize="yes"
/>
```

!! Grid-Track Resizing

`mode="grid-track"` is for CSS Grid layouts where columns and rows are controlled by CSS variables such as:

```css
--btc-rgrid-columns-template: var(--btc-rgrid-col-1, 25%) var(--btc-rgrid-col-2, 25%) var(--btc-rgrid-col-3, 25%) var(--btc-rgrid-col-4, 25%);
--btc-rgrid-rows-template: var(--btc-rgrid-row-1, 20%) var(--btc-rgrid-row-2, 20%) var(--btc-rgrid-row-3, 20%) var(--btc-rgrid-row-4, 20%) var(--btc-rgrid-row-5, 20%);
```

A grid-track handle resizes a ''boundary'' between two adjacent tracks.

For columns:

```text
column N grows   -> column N+1 shrinks
column N shrinks -> column N+1 grows
```

For rows:

```text
row N grows   -> row N+1 shrinks
row N shrinks -> row N+1 grows
```

The pair total is preserved, so the overall grid remains stable. This is different from resizing a cell element. The visual handle may appear at the edge of a cell, but the resized thing is the underlying grid track boundary.

!!! Axis

`gridTrackAxis` controls whether the resizer works on columns or rows.

|!Axis|!Pointer axis|!Template|!CSS variables|!State tiddlers|
|`column`|`clientX` / horizontal|`grid-template-columns`|`--btc-rgrid-col-N`|`<statePrefix>/col-N`|
|`row`|`clientY` / vertical|`grid-template-rows`|`--btc-rgrid-row-N`|`<statePrefix>/row-N`|

Column mode is the default for backwards compatibility.

!!! Why freeze on start and end?

A CSS Grid table often starts with percentage or `fr` defaults. After manual resizing, pixel tracks are more stable because they match the browser's computed layout exactly. `gridTrackFreezeOnStart="yes"` freezes all current tracks to exact pixel variables before the drag moves. `gridTrackFreezeOnEnd="yes"` saves the final browser-resolved track values on pointerup.

Recommended settings:

```html
<$resizer
  mode="grid-track"
  gridTrackLiveUnit="px"
  gridTrackSaveUnit="px"
  gridTrackFreezeOnStart="yes"
  gridTrackFreezeOnEnd="yes"
/>
```

!!! Handle placement

For a cell with `col="2"` and `colspan="3"`, the right boundary is after column 4:

```text
boundaryIndex = col + colspan - 1
```

So the column handle should use:

```html
gridTrackAxis="column"
gridTrackIndex="4"
```

For a cell with `row="2"` and `rowspan="3"`, the bottom boundary is after row 4:

```text
rowBoundaryIndex = row + rowspan - 1
```

So the row handle should use:

```html
gridTrackAxis="row"
gridTrackIndex="4"
```

!!! Overlay handles

Earlier versions rendered handles as children of cells. That can cause hit-testing problems because the neighboring grid cell can cover part of the handle.

The current table procedures use overlay handles: the handle is a separate grid item placed over the same grid area as the cell. The overlay slot has `pointer-events:none`, while the actual handle has `pointer-events:auto`.

Conceptually:

```html
<div class="btc-rgrid-cell btc-rgrid-cell-real">...</div>
<div class="btc-rgrid-overlay-slot"> <$resizer .../> </div>
```

This keeps the handle above all cells and avoids asymmetric hover behavior.

!! CSS Grid Table Procedures

The plugin includes Wikitext procedures that build CSS Grid table-like layouts. These are not native HTML `<table>` elements. They are CSS Grid layouts, which means merged cells are handled naturally with `grid-area`, and column/row resizing is done by changing the underlying grid track variables.

The current procedure families are:

|!Procedure|!Purpose|
|`btc.rgrid.track.table`|Manual grid table. Cells are manually transcluded through `btc.rgrid.track.cell` or `btc.rgrid.track.header`. Columns are resizable.|
|`btc.rgrid.placed.table`|Tiddler-driven placed table. A filter returns cell tiddlers with `row`, `col`, `rowspan`, and `colspan` fields. Columns are resizable.|
|`btc.rgrid.xy.table`|Tiddler-driven X/Y table. A filter returns cell tiddlers with `row`, `col`, `rowspan`, and `colspan` fields. Columns and rows are resizable.|

All RGrid table procedures use the same base CSS classes:

```text
btc-rgrid-table
btc-rgrid-content
btc-rgrid-cell
btc-rgrid-cell-content
```

The placed and xy procedures also use overlay handle classes:

```text
btc-rgrid-overlay-slot
btc-rgrid-overlay-resizer
btc-rgrid-column-overlay-resizer
btc-rgrid-row-overlay-resizer
```

The current model separates three concepts:

* ''CSS track size'': the actual grid column/row size used by `grid-template-columns` or `grid-template-rows`.
* ''Resizer constraint'': the minimum/maximum used while dragging a grid-track boundary.
* ''Cell content styling'': padding, background, headers, footers, and scroll behavior inside each cell.

!!! Track fallback priority

Column and row sizes can come from several places. The current intended priority is:

```text
saved state tiddler
→ explicit positional defaults (`colDefaults` / `rowDefaults`, where supported)
→ filler-track fallback (`fillLastColumn` / `fillLastRow`)
→ global default size (`defaultColSize` / `defaultRowSize`)
```

For `btc.rgrid.track.table` and `btc.rgrid.placed.table`, there are no `colDefaults`, so the column priority is:

```text
saved column state
→ `fillLastColumn` / `lastColSize`
→ `defaultColSize`
```

For `btc.rgrid.xy.table`, the column priority is:

```text
saved column state
→ `colDefaults` item
→ `fillLastColumn` / `lastColSize`
→ `defaultColSize`
```

and the row priority is:

```text
saved row state
→ `rowDefaults` item
→ `fillLastRow` / `lastRowSize`
→ `defaultRowSize`
```

This matters. For example:

```html
rowDefaults="4rem default default default 6rem"
fillLastRow="yes"
lastRowSize="1fr"
```

The last row defaults to `6rem`, not `1fr`, because the explicit `rowDefaults` item wins over the filler fallback.

!!! `colMinWidth` vs `minColSize`

`colMinWidth` and `minColSize` are deliberately different:

|!Attribute|!Layer|!Purpose|
|`colMinWidth`|CSS Grid layout|The minimum used inside `minmax(...)`. It controls how small the browser may render a column.|
|`minColSize`|Resizer logic|The minimum size allowed while dragging a column boundary.|

Use both when you want robust behavior:

```html
colMinWidth="6rem"
minColSize="6rem"
```

`colMinWidth="0"` preserves the older behavior where CSS Grid may shrink a column all the way down to zero if the container is too small.

!!! Filler tracks and container growth

When every column has been frozen to pixels, the grid will not naturally absorb extra horizontal space. `fillLastColumn="yes"` keeps the last column elastic by using `lastColSize`, usually `1fr`, when no saved state or explicit default wins.

For XY tables, the same idea applies vertically. `fillLastRow="yes"` lets the last row absorb extra height by using `lastRowSize`, usually `1fr`, when no saved state or explicit row default wins.

Filler tracks help when the container grows. They do not solve the opposite case where the container becomes smaller than the sum of fixed track sizes. In that case the grid must overflow, scroll, or clip depending on CSS.

!!! Manual track table: `btc.rgrid.track.table`

The manual track table is useful when you want to define cells directly in Wikitext. It is column-resizable only.

!!!! Signature

```html
<$transclude
  $variable="btc.rgrid.track.table"
  gridId="default"
  columns="4"
  statePrefix="$:/state/btc/resizer/rgrid/default"
  defaultColSize=""
  colMinWidth="0"
  fillLastColumn="yes"
  lastColSize="1fr"
  minColSize="4%"
  maxColSize="90%"
  unit="%"
  gap="0.25rem"
  rowMinHeight="3rem"
  class=""
  content=""
/>
```

!!!! Attributes

|!Attribute|!Description|!Default|
|`gridId`|Unique grid instance id. Creates class `.btc-rgrid-instance-<gridId>`.|`default`|
|`columns`|Number of grid columns.|`4`|
|`statePrefix`|Prefix for saved column state tiddlers.|`$:/state/btc/resizer/rgrid/default`|
|`defaultColSize`|Global fallback column size. If blank, the procedure calculates `100 / columns %`.|blank|
|`colMinWidth`|CSS-level minimum used in `minmax(var(--btc-rgrid-col-min-width, ...), ...)` for each column.|`0`|
|`fillLastColumn`|When `yes`, the last column can use `lastColSize` as an elastic fallback.|`yes`|
|`lastColSize`|Fallback size for the last column when `fillLastColumn="yes"` and no saved state wins.|`1fr`|
|`minColSize`|Minimum size for either track in a resized column pair.|`4%`|
|`maxColSize`|Maximum size for the primary column track.|`90%`|
|`unit`|Unit used by the column resizer for constraints and saved values.|`%`|
|`gap`|Grid/visual gap value used by the manual table CSS.|`0.25rem`|
|`rowMinHeight`|Minimum row height used by auto-created rows.|`3rem`|
|`class`|Additional class appended to `.btc-rgrid-table`.|blank|
|`content`|Variable containing the manually rendered cells.|blank|

!!!! Manual cells

`btc.rgrid.track.cell`:

```html
<$transclude
  $variable="btc.rgrid.track.cell"
  col="1"
  row="1"
  colSpan="1"
  rowSpan="1"
  last="no"
  resize="yes"
  class=""
  title=""
  content=""
  cellPadding=""
/>
```

`btc.rgrid.track.header` wraps `btc.rgrid.track.cell` and adds the header class.

|!Attribute|!Description|!Default|
|`col`|Grid column start.|`auto`|
|`row`|Grid row start.|`auto`|
|`colSpan`|Number of columns spanned.|`1`|
|`rowSpan`|Number of rows spanned.|`1`|
|`last`|Set to `yes` for the last column cell to suppress a right-edge handle.|`no`|
|`resize`|Whether to render a column handle for this cell.|`yes`|
|`class`|Additional cell classes.|blank|
|`title`|Optional visible title inside the cell.|blank|
|`content`|Variable transcluded as the cell content.|blank|
|`cellPadding`|Optional per-cell padding. If blank/default, CSS fallback is used.|blank|

!!!! Example

```html
<$transclude
  $variable="btc.rgrid.track.table"
  gridId="manual-demo"
  columns="4"
  statePrefix="$:/state/btc/rgrid/manual-demo"
  defaultColSize="25%"
  colMinWidth="5rem"
  fillLastColumn="yes"
  lastColSize="1fr"
  gap="0.25rem"
  rowMinHeight="3rem"
  content="""
<$transclude $variable="btc.rgrid.track.header" col="1" row="1" colSpan="2" content="Header"/>
<$transclude $variable="btc.rgrid.track.cell" col="3" row="1" content="Cell 3"/>
<$transclude $variable="btc.rgrid.track.cell" col="4" row="1" last="yes" content="Cell 4"/>
"""
/>
```

!! Placed Tiddler Grid Tables: `btc.rgrid.placed.table`

`btc.rgrid.placed.table` creates a grid from a filter-selected set of cell tiddlers. It supports explicit placement, colspan, rowspan, ghost cells, per-cell padding, configurable transclusion mode, draft exclusion, CSS-level column minimums, adaptive last-column filling, and overlay column resize handles.

It resizes columns only.

!!! Signature

```html
<$transclude
  $variable="btc.rgrid.placed.table"
  gridId="placed-default"
  cellFilter="[tag[TableCell]]"
  columns="4"
  rows="4"
  statePrefix="$:/state/btc/rgrid/placed/default"
  defaultColSize=""
  defaultRowSize="auto"
  colMinWidth="0"
  fillLastColumn="yes"
  lastColSize="1fr"
  rowMinHeight="3rem"
  cellGap="0.35rem"
  defaultCellPadding="0.75em 0.95em"
  cellPaddingDefaults=""
  cellPaddingField="padding"
  defaultCellMode="block"
  cellModeField="cellmode"
  minColSize="4%"
  maxColSize="90%"
  unit="%"
  class=""
  sortField="order"
  showTitles="no"
/>
```

!!! Attributes

|!Attribute|!Description|!Default|
|`gridId`|Unique grid instance id. Creates class `.btc-rgrid-instance-<gridId>` and is used by the overlay resizers as selector target.|`placed-default`|
|`cellFilter`|Filter returning the real cell tiddlers. The procedure excludes drafts with `!is[draft]` wherever it lists this filter.|`[tag[TableCell]]`|
|`columns`|Number of grid columns.|`4`|
|`rows`|Number of grid rows.|`4`|
|`statePrefix`|Prefix for persisted column widths. Column state tiddlers are `<statePrefix>/col-1`, `<statePrefix>/col-2`, etc.|`$:/state/btc/rgrid/placed/default`|
|`defaultColSize`|Fallback column size when no persisted column state exists. If blank, the procedure calculates `100 / columns %`.|blank|
|`defaultRowSize`|Default row track size.|`auto`|
|`colMinWidth`|CSS-level minimum width for every column. Used in the grid template `minmax(...)` expression.|`0`|
|`fillLastColumn`|When `yes`, the last column can use `lastColSize` as an elastic fallback if no saved state wins.|`yes`|
|`lastColSize`|Fallback size for the last column when `fillLastColumn="yes"`.|`1fr`|
|`rowMinHeight`|Minimum row height used by the row template.|`3rem`|
|`cellGap`|Visual spacing between cells. The actual CSS grid gap should stay `0`; visual spacing is created by wrapper padding.|`0.35rem`|
|`defaultCellPadding`|Global fallback padding for real cell content.|`0.75em 0.95em`|
|`cellPaddingDefaults`|Semicolon-separated row-major padding fallback list. Use `default` to fall back to `defaultCellPadding` for that coordinate.|blank|
|`cellPaddingField`|Field name read from each cell tiddler for per-cell padding.|`padding`|
|`defaultCellMode`|Default transclusion mode for cell text. Valid values: `block` and `inline`.|`block`|
|`cellModeField`|Field name read from each cell tiddler for per-cell transclusion mode.|`cellmode`|
|`minColSize`|Minimum size for either track in a resized column pair. This is a resizer constraint, not the CSS grid minimum.|`4%`|
|`maxColSize`|Maximum size for the primary column track.|`90%`|
|`unit`|Unit used by the column resizer for constraints and saved values.|`%`|
|`class`|Additional class appended to `.btc-rgrid-table`.|blank|
|`sortField`|Field used to sort real cell tiddlers before rendering.|`order`|
|`showTitles`|When `yes`, renders a linked title inside each real cell.|`no`|

!!! Column fallback order

For `btc.rgrid.placed.table`, the column fallback order is:

# saved state tiddler `<statePrefix>/col-N`
# `lastColSize`, only when `fillLastColumn="yes"` and `N` is the last column
# `defaultColSize`

If `defaultColSize` is blank, it is calculated as `100 / columns %`.

!!! Cell tiddler fields

|!Field/tag|!Meaning|!Fallback|
|`row`|1-based row start.|Required for real cells.|
|`col`|1-based column start.|Required for real cells.|
|`rowspan`|Number of rows spanned by the cell.|`1`|
|`colspan`|Number of columns spanned by the cell.|`1`|
|`padding`|Per-cell padding, unless `cellPaddingField` is changed.|Falls back to `cellPaddingDefaults`, then `defaultCellPadding`.|
|`cellmode`|Per-cell transclusion mode, unless `cellModeField` is changed.|Falls back to `defaultCellMode`, then `block`.|
|`order`|Sort key when `sortField="order"`.|Optional.|
|Tag `Header`|Adds class `btc-rgrid-cell-header`.|Optional.|
|Tag `Footer`|Adds class `btc-rgrid-cell-footer`.|Optional.|
|Tag `Muted`|Adds class `btc-rgrid-cell-muted`.|Optional.|

The text of the cell tiddler is transcluded as the cell content.

!!! Draft exclusion

The procedure excludes draft tiddlers with `!is[draft]` wherever `cellFilter` is listed. Draft cell tiddlers should not:

* participate in occupied-cell detection,
* render as real cells,
* create overlay handles.

!!! Ghost cells

For every declared coordinate, the procedure checks whether any real cell covers it. If no real cell covers the coordinate, a ghost cell is rendered.

A real cell suppresses all ghosts covered by its area:

```text
row <= coordinate row <= row + rowspan - 1
col <= coordinate col <= col + colspan - 1
```

Ghost cells also get overlay column handles unless their coordinate is in the last column.

!!! Overlay column handles

Placed-table overlay handles are rendered as separate siblings after the visible cells. They use the same grid coordinate as the real/ghost cell whose boundary they represent.

For a real cell:

```text
boundaryIndex = col + colspan - 1
```

For a ghost cell:

```text
boundaryIndex = col
```

No handle is rendered when `boundaryIndex >= columns`.

!!! Padding

Padding can be defined in three levels:

# cell tiddler field named by `cellPaddingField`
# `cellPaddingDefaults` row-major item
# `defaultCellPadding`

`cellPaddingDefaults` uses semicolons so each padding value may contain spaces:

```html
cellPaddingDefaults="1em 1.25em;default;0.4em 0.6em;0;default"
```

The index is row-major:

|!Index|!Coordinate|
|1|row 1, col 1|
|2|row 1, col 2|
|3|row 1, col 3|
|4|row 1, col 4|
|5|row 2, col 1|

The word `default` means “use `defaultCellPadding` for this coordinate.”

!!! Cell rendering mode

Cell content is transcluded from the cell tiddler text.

Modes:

|!Mode|!Meaning|
|`block`|Normal Wikitext block rendering. Good for headings, lists, tables, paragraphs. May create `<p>` elements for plain text.|
|`inline`|Inline rendering. Useful for compact plain cells where block paragraphs are not wanted.|

Fallback order:

# cell tiddler field named by `cellModeField`
# `defaultCellMode`
# `block`

Cell field example:

```text
cellmode: inline
```

!!! Example

```html
<$transclude
  $variable="btc.rgrid.placed.table"
  gridId="project-table"
  cellFilter="[tag[ProjectTableCell]]"
  columns="4"
  rows="6"
  statePrefix="$:/state/project-table"
  defaultColSize="25%"
  defaultRowSize="auto"
  colMinWidth="5rem"
  fillLastColumn="yes"
  lastColSize="1fr"
  cellGap="0.45rem"
  defaultCellPadding="0.75em 0.95em"
  cellPaddingDefaults="1em;default;0.4em 0.6em;default"
  defaultCellMode="block"
  minColSize="5rem"
  maxColSize="80%"
  unit="%"
  showTitles="no"
/>
```

!! XY Resizable Grid Tables: `btc.rgrid.xy.table`

`btc.rgrid.xy.table` creates a placed grid from a filter-selected set of cell tiddlers. It supports explicit placement, colspan, rowspan, ghost cells, per-column and per-row fallback sizes, per-cell padding, configurable transclusion mode, draft exclusion, CSS-level column minimums, adaptive last-column filling, adaptive last-row filling, overlay column resize handles, and overlay row resize handles.

It can resize columns, rows, or both.

!!! Signature

```html
<$transclude
  $variable="btc.rgrid.xy.table"
  gridId="xy-default"
  cellFilter="[tag[TableCell]]"
  columns="4"
  rows="4"
  statePrefix="$:/state/btc/rgrid/xy/default"
  defaultColSize=""
  defaultRowSize=""
  colDefaults=""
  rowDefaults=""
  colMinWidth="0"
  fillLastColumn="yes"
  lastColSize="1fr"
  fillLastRow="yes"
  lastRowSize="1fr"
  defaultCellPadding="0.75em 0.95em"
  cellPaddingDefaults=""
  cellPaddingField="padding"
  defaultCellMode="block"
  cellModeField="cellmode"
  rowMinHeight="3rem"
  cellGap="0.35rem"
  height="32rem"
  resizeColumns="yes"
  resizeRows="yes"
  minColSize="4%"
  maxColSize="90%"
  minRowSize="2rem"
  maxRowSize="80%"
  colUnit="%"
  rowUnit="px"
  class=""
  sortField="order"
  showTitles="no"
/>
```

!!! Attributes

|!Attribute|!Description|!Default|
|`gridId`|Unique grid instance id. Creates class `.btc-rgrid-instance-<gridId>` and is used by overlay resizers as selector target.|`xy-default`|
|`cellFilter`|Filter returning the real cell tiddlers. The procedure excludes drafts with `!is[draft]` wherever it lists this filter.|`[tag[TableCell]]`|
|`columns`|Number of grid columns.|`4`|
|`rows`|Number of grid rows.|`4`|
|`statePrefix`|Prefix for persisted track sizes. Columns use `<statePrefix>/col-N`; rows use `<statePrefix>/row-N`.|`$:/state/btc/rgrid/xy/default`|
|`defaultColSize`|Global fallback column size. If blank, the procedure calculates `100 / columns %`.|blank|
|`defaultRowSize`|Global fallback row size. If blank, the procedure calculates `100 / rows %`.|blank|
|`colDefaults`|Space-separated positional fallback list for columns. Use `default` to fall back to `defaultColSize` for that column.|blank|
|`rowDefaults`|Space-separated positional fallback list for rows. Use `default` to fall back to `defaultRowSize` for that row.|blank|
|`colMinWidth`|CSS-level minimum width for every column. Used in the grid template `minmax(...)` expression.|`0`|
|`fillLastColumn`|When `yes`, the last column can use `lastColSize` as an elastic fallback if no saved state or explicit `colDefaults` item wins.|`yes`|
|`lastColSize`|Fallback size for the last column when `fillLastColumn="yes"`.|`1fr`|
|`fillLastRow`|When `yes`, the last row can use `lastRowSize` as an elastic fallback if no saved state or explicit `rowDefaults` item wins.|`yes`|
|`lastRowSize`|Fallback size for the last row when `fillLastRow="yes"`.|`1fr`|
|`defaultCellPadding`|Global fallback padding for real cell content.|`0.75em 0.95em`|
|`cellPaddingDefaults`|Semicolon-separated row-major padding fallback list. Use `default` to fall back to `defaultCellPadding` for that coordinate.|blank|
|`cellPaddingField`|Field name read from each cell tiddler for per-cell padding.|`padding`|
|`defaultCellMode`|Default transclusion mode for cell text. Valid values: `block` and `inline`.|`block`|
|`cellModeField`|Field name read from each cell tiddler for per-cell transclusion mode.|`cellmode`|
|`rowMinHeight`|Minimum row height used by the row template.|`3rem`|
|`cellGap`|Visual spacing between cells. The actual CSS grid gap should stay `0`; visual spacing is created by wrapper padding.|`0.35rem`|
|`height`|Fixed grid height used when row resizing is enabled. Use values like `32rem`, `75vh`, or `100vh`.|`32rem`|
|`resizeColumns`|Enable column overlay handles. Use `yes` or `no`.|`yes`|
|`resizeRows`|Enable row overlay handles. Use `yes` or `no`.|`yes`|
|`minColSize`|Minimum size for either track in a resized column pair. This is a resizer constraint, not the CSS grid minimum.|`4%`|
|`maxColSize`|Maximum size for the primary column track.|`90%`|
|`minRowSize`|Minimum size for either track in a resized row pair.|`2rem`|
|`maxRowSize`|Maximum size for the primary row track.|`80%`|
|`colUnit`|Unit used by the column resizer for constraints and saved values.|`%`|
|`rowUnit`|Unit used by the row resizer for constraints and saved values.|`px`|
|`class`|Additional class appended to `.btc-rgrid-table`.|blank|
|`sortField`|Field used to sort real cell tiddlers before rendering.|`order`|
|`showTitles`|When `yes`, renders a linked title inside each real cell.|`no`|

!!! Cell tiddler fields

`btc.rgrid.xy.table` uses the same cell fields as `btc.rgrid.placed.table`:

|!Field/tag|!Meaning|!Fallback|
|`row`|1-based row start.|Required for real cells.|
|`col`|1-based column start.|Required for real cells.|
|`rowspan`|Number of rows spanned by the cell.|`1`|
|`colspan`|Number of columns spanned by the cell.|`1`|
|`padding`|Per-cell padding, unless `cellPaddingField` is changed.|Falls back to `cellPaddingDefaults`, then `defaultCellPadding`.|
|`cellmode`|Per-cell transclusion mode, unless `cellModeField` is changed.|Falls back to `defaultCellMode`, then `block`.|
|`order`|Sort key when `sortField="order"`.|Optional.|
|Tag `Header`|Adds class `btc-rgrid-cell-header`.|Optional.|
|Tag `Footer`|Adds class `btc-rgrid-cell-footer`.|Optional.|
|Tag `Muted`|Adds class `btc-rgrid-cell-muted`.|Optional.|

!!! Column and row defaults

`colDefaults` and `rowDefaults` are positional fallback lists.

```html
colDefaults="14rem default 2fr 18rem"
rowDefaults="4rem default default default 6rem"
```

The word `default` means “continue to the next fallback”, which usually means the global default size, or the filler fallback when the track is the last track and no explicit positional value is present.

Column example:

|!Column|!Fallback|
|1|`14rem`|
|2|`defaultColSize` or later fallback|
|3|`2fr`|
|4|`18rem`|

Row example:

|!Row|!Fallback|
|1|`4rem`|
|2|`defaultRowSize` or later fallback|
|3|`defaultRowSize` or later fallback|
|4|`defaultRowSize` or later fallback|
|5|`6rem`|

Persisted state tiddlers override these defaults:

```text
$:/state/btc/rgrid/xy-demo/col-1
$:/state/btc/rgrid/xy-demo/row-1
```

Column fallback order:

# saved state tiddler `<statePrefix>/col-N`
# explicit `colDefaults` item for column `N`
# `lastColSize`, only when `fillLastColumn="yes"` and `N` is the last column
# `defaultColSize`

Row fallback order:

# saved state tiddler `<statePrefix>/row-N`
# explicit `rowDefaults` item for row `N`
# `lastRowSize`, only when `fillLastRow="yes"` and `N` is the last row
# `defaultRowSize`

Example:

```html
rowDefaults="4rem default default default 6rem"
fillLastRow="yes"
lastRowSize="1fr"
```

The last row uses `6rem`, not `1fr`, because the explicit row default wins over the filler fallback.

!!! Full-height tables

For full-height tables, use a real table height and non-`auto` row tracks.

Good:

```html
height="100vh"
defaultRowSize="1fr"
fillLastRow="yes"
lastRowSize="1fr"
```

or:

```html
height="100vh"
rowDefaults="4rem default default default 6rem"
defaultRowSize="1fr"
fillLastRow="yes"
lastRowSize="1fr"
```

Avoid:

```html
defaultRowSize="auto"
```

when you expect rows to fill the height. `auto` means “fit content”, not “fill available space”.

If the container becomes smaller than the sum of fixed row heights, the grid will overflow. `fillLastRow` helps absorb extra height; it does not compress fixed rows below their minimums.

!!! Row and column overlay handles

For real cells:

```text
column boundary = col + colspan - 1
row boundary    = row + rowspan - 1
```

For ghost cells:

```text
column boundary = col
row boundary    = row
```

Column handles are not rendered for the last column boundary. Row handles are not rendered for the last row boundary.

!!! Padding and cell mode

Padding and cell mode work the same as in `btc.rgrid.placed.table`.

Padding fallback order:

# cell tiddler field named by `cellPaddingField`
# `cellPaddingDefaults` row-major item
# `defaultCellPadding`

Cell mode fallback order:

# cell tiddler field named by `cellModeField`
# `defaultCellMode`
# `block`

!!! Example

```html
<$transclude
  $variable="btc.rgrid.xy.table"
  gridId="xy-dashboard"
  cellFilter="[tag[XYDashboardCell]]"
  columns="4"
  rows="5"
  statePrefix="$:/state/btc/rgrid/xy-dashboard"
  defaultColSize="1fr"
  defaultRowSize="1fr"
  colDefaults="14rem default 2fr 18rem"
  rowDefaults="4rem default default default 6rem"
  colMinWidth="6rem"
  fillLastColumn="yes"
  lastColSize="1fr"
  fillLastRow="yes"
  lastRowSize="1fr"
  defaultCellPadding="0.75em 0.95em"
  cellPaddingDefaults="1em;default;0.4em 0.6em;default"
  defaultCellMode="block"
  height="100vh"
  resizeColumns="yes"
  resizeRows="yes"
  minColSize="6rem"
  maxColSize="80%"
  minRowSize="3rem"
  maxRowSize="24rem"
  colUnit="%"
  rowUnit="px"
  showTitles="yes"
/>
```

!! Cell Tiddler Example

```text
title: Dashboard/Cell 1
tags: XYDashboardCell Header
row: 1
col: 1
rowspan: 1
colspan: 2
order: 10
padding: 1em 1.25em
cellmode: block

!! Header

This cell spans two columns.
```

!! RGrid CSS Notes

The essential CSS model is:

```css
.btc-rgrid-table {
  --btc-rgrid-columns-template: repeat(4, minmax(0, 1fr));
  --btc-rgrid-rows-template: repeat(4, minmax(3rem, auto));
  --btc-rgrid-col-min-width: 0;
  --btc-rgrid-row-min-height: 3rem;
  --btc-rgrid-cell-gap: 0.35rem;
  --btc-rgrid-cell-padding: 0.75em 0.95em;
}

.btc-rgrid-content {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: var(--btc-rgrid-columns-template);
  grid-template-rows: var(--btc-rgrid-rows-template);
  gap: 0;
}

.btc-rgrid-cell-content {
  padding: var(--btc-rgrid-cell-padding, 0.75em 0.95em);
  min-width: 0;
  min-height: 0;
  overflow: auto;
}
```

Column templates should use a CSS minimum:

```css
minmax(var(--btc-rgrid-col-min-width, 0), var(--btc-rgrid-col-1, 1fr))
```

Row templates should use a CSS minimum:

```css
minmax(var(--btc-rgrid-row-min-height), var(--btc-rgrid-row-1, 1fr))
```

For row-resizable tables, this is usually useful:

```css
.btc-rgrid-table[data-resize-rows="yes"] {
  height: var(--btc-rgrid-height);
  max-height: var(--btc-rgrid-height);
  overflow: auto;
}

.btc-rgrid-table[data-resize-rows="yes"] > .btc-rgrid-content {
  min-height: 100%;
}
```

Overlay handles should sit above cells:

```css
.btc-rgrid-overlay-slot {
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1000;
  pointer-events: none;
  overflow: visible;
}

.btc-rgrid-overlay-slot > .tc-resizer {
  pointer-events: auto;
}
```


!! Snap Points

Snap points let the drag value lock to useful sizes when the pointer is close enough.

Example:

```html
<$resizer
  tiddler="$:/state/sidebar/width"
  unit="rem"
  min="0px"
  max="42rem"
  snap="0px 14rem 22rem 34rem"
  snapDistance="10px"
/>
```

Useful snap patterns:

```html
snap="0px 16rem 24rem 32rem"
snap="25% 33.333333% 50% 66.666667% 75%"
snap="calc(100vw - 40rem) calc(100vw - 24rem)"
```

Separators accepted by the parser:

```text
space, comma, semicolon, pipe, newline
```

Because `calc()` may contain spaces, keep complex `calc()` expressions simple and test them in the browser console if a snap point does not behave as expected.

!!! Snap and constraints

The resize flow applies min/max constraints and snap logic as part of the value calculation. If a snap point lies outside `min`/`max`, the final value may still be constrained.

!!! Snap and haptics

```html
<$resizer
  snap="0px 20rem 50%"
  snapHaptic="yes"
  hapticFeedback="yes"
/>
```

Haptic feedback depends on browser and device support. Desktop browsers commonly ignore vibration.

!! Preset Cycling

Preset cycling lets a double-click or double-tap step through named layout states.

```html
<$resizer
  tiddler="$:/state/sidebar/width"
  selector=".sidebar"
  property="flexBasis"
  unit="rem"
  live="yes"
  presetCycle="yes"
  presets="closed:0px;narrow:14rem;normal:22rem;wide:34rem"
  presetTiddler="$:/state/sidebar/mode"
  presetIndexTiddler="$:/state/sidebar/preset-index"
/>
```

The parser accepts:

```text
closed:0px;narrow:14rem;normal:22rem;wide:34rem
```

or:

```text
closed:0px
narrow:14rem
normal:22rem
wide:34rem
```

Plain unnamed presets also work:

```html
presets="0px;14rem;22rem;34rem"
```

In that case, preset names are generated from the zero-based index.

!!! Double-click priority

Preset cycling does not break existing custom double-click behavior. The order is:

```text
1. dblClickActions, if present
2. presetCycle="yes" with usable presets
3. built-in reset behavior
```

So if you want preset cycling, do not also set `dblClickActions` on the same handle unless you intentionally want to override the built-in preset feature.

!! CSS Variable Publishing

CSS variable publishing lets the widget update custom properties while still writing tiddler state.

!!! Root-level variable

```html
<$resizer
  tiddler="$:/state/sidebar/width"
  selector=".sidebar"
  property="flexBasis"
  unit="rem"
  cssVariable="--btc-sidebar-width"
  cssVariableTarget="root"
  live="yes"
/>
```

```css
.sidebar {
  flex: 0 0 var(--btc-sidebar-width, 22rem);
}
```

!!! Parent-level variable

```html
<$resizer
  selector=".sidebar"
  cssVariable="--sidebar-width"
  cssVariableTarget="parent"
/>
```

This publishes the variable on the target element's parent.

!!! Selector target

```html
<$resizer
  selector=".sidebar"
  cssVariable="--sidebar-width"
  cssVariableTarget="selector"
  cssVariableSelector=".layout-root"
/>
```

You can also pass a selector directly as `cssVariableTarget`:

```html
<$resizer
  selector=".sidebar"
  cssVariable="--sidebar-width"
  cssVariableTarget=".layout-root"
/>
```

!!! Split-pair variables

```html
<$resizer
  mode="split-pair"
  direction="horizontal"
  element="previousSibling"
  leftTiddler="$:/state/left"
  rightTiddler="$:/state/right"
  leftCssVariable="--left-width"
  rightCssVariable="--right-width"
  cssVariableTarget="root"
  splitPairLiveResize="yes"
/>
```

For vertical layouts:

```html
<$resizer
  mode="split-pair"
  direction="vertical"
  topCssVariable="--top-height"
  bottomCssVariable="--bottom-height"
/>
```

!! Live DOM Resizing

Normal `live="yes"` directly updates the selected target's CSS property while dragging.

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  selector=".tc-sidebar"
  property="width"
  tiddler="$:/state/sidebar/width"
  live="yes"
/>
```

For flex layouts, prefer:

```html
property="flexBasis"
```

For `split-pair`, prefer:

```html
splitPairLiveResize="yes"
splitPairSave="end"
```

This updates both panes and their `flex-basis` while dragging, but saves the final state tiddlers only once at the end of the drag.

For `table-column`, prefer:

```html
tableColumnLiveResize="yes"
tableColumnSave="end"
```

This updates the `<col>` while dragging, then writes the final width once.

!! Double-Click Reset

Double-click a resizer handle to reset the value, unless `dblClickActions` or preset cycling is active.

!!! Reset to default

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/panel/width"
  default="300px"
  resetTo="default"
/>
```

!!! Reset to minimum

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/panel/width"
  min="200px"
  resetTo="min"
/>
```

!!! Reset to maximum

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/panel/width"
  max="800px"
  resetTo="max"
/>
```

!!! Reset to custom value

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/panel/width"
  resetTo="custom"
  resetValue="420px"
/>
```

!!! Run custom double-click actions

`dblClickActions` overrides preset cycling and built-in reset behavior.

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/panel/width"
  dblClickActions="""
    <$action-log message="Panel double-clicked" value=<<tv-action-value>>/>
  """
/>
```

!! CSS `calc()` Support

The widget supports `calc()` in `min`, `max`, `default`, snap points, and `snapDistance`.

```html
<$resizer
  direction="horizontal"
  tiddler="$:/state/panel/width"
  default="calc(50vw - 100px)"
  min="calc(200px + handleWidth)"
  max="calc(100vw - 350px - handleWidth)"
  snap="calc(100vw - 40rem) 50% 75%"
  snapDistance="calc(handleSize + 4px)"
/>
```

!!! Special calc variables

|!Variable|!Meaning|
|`handleSize`|Computed width or height of the handle, depending on direction.|
|`handleWidth`|Alias for `handleSize`.|
|`handleHeight`|Alias for `handleSize`.|

Examples:

```html
<$resizer min="calc(handleSize + 20px)" />
<$resizer max="calc(100% - handleSize)" />
<$resizer default="calc(50% - handleSize / 2)" />
```

The `calc()` evaluator is intentionally limited. It supports nested `calc()`, parentheses, `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, supported units, and the handle variables above. It is not a complete browser-grade CSS parser.

!! Units and Conversion

Supported units:

```text
px, %, em, rem, vh, vw, vmin, vmax
```

The widget performs drag math in pixels because pointer movement is measured in pixels. It then converts the result back to the configured or original unit.

Precision rules:

|!Unit|!Formatting|
|`%`|stable percentage precision; use six decimals for Wikitext-generated layout values|
|`px`|pixel value with decimal/subpixel precision|
|`em`, `rem`|font-relative decimal precision|
|`vh`, `vw`, `vmin`, `vmax`|viewport-relative decimal precision|

For Wikitext-generated percentages, use `fixed[6]` before appending `%`:

```tw
cellWidth={{{ [[100]divide<columns>fixed[6]addsuffix[%]] }}}
```

This avoids noisy floating-point values such as `33.333333333333336%` while preserving enough precision for stable layouts.

!! Constraints

!!! Normal modes

`min` and `max` constrain the target value. For multiple tiddlers, the delta is clamped so all target values stay within their constraints.

!!! Split-pair mode

`min` applies to both panes in the pair. The first pane cannot grow so far that the second pane becomes smaller than `min`.

Conceptually:

```text
primaryMin = min
secondaryMin = min
primaryMax = pairSize - secondaryMin
```

If `max` is set, it additionally limits the primary pane.

For most split-pair layouts, prefer setting only `min` first. Add `max` only when you need a hard maximum for the first pane.

!!! Table-column mode

`min` and `max` constrain the column width. If `snap` is also set, the snapped value is still subject to the effective min/max range.

!! Styling

The widget renders a `div` with class:

```text
tc-resizer
```

plus any additional class from the `class` attribute.

During interaction:

|!Class|!Applied to|!Meaning|
|`tc-resizer-active`|resizer handle|The handle is being dragged.|
|`tc-resizer-disabled`|resizer handle|The handle is disabled.|
|`tc-resizing`|`body`|A resize operation is active.|

Example styling:

```css
.tc-resizer {
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1000;
  background: transparent;
  touch-action: none;
  user-select: none;
}

.tc-resizer[data-direction="horizontal"] {
  width: 8px;
  cursor: ew-resize;
}

.tc-resizer[data-direction="vertical"] {
  height: 8px;
  cursor: ns-resize;
}

.tc-resizer:hover,
.tc-resizer-active {
  background: rgba(127, 127, 127, 0.25);
}

.tc-resizer-disabled {
  opacity: 0.5;
  cursor: not-allowed;
}

.tc-resizing * {
  user-select: none !important;
}
```

!!! Handle style examples

The widget adds:

```html
data-handle-style="grip"
```

when `handleStyle="grip"` is used. You can style it with CSS:

```css
.tc-resizer[data-handle-style="grip"]::after {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  inset: 2px;
  border-radius: 999px;
  background: currentColor;
  opacity: 0.25;
}
```

!!! Table-column handle styling

If you render a resizer inside a table header, keep the handle small and positioned at the right edge:

```css
th .tc-resizer[data-direction="horizontal"] {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: -4px;
  width: 8px;
  height: 100%;
  cursor: col-resize;
}

th {
  position: relative;
}
```

!!! CSS Grid table handle styling

For `mode="grid-track"`, the handle is a normal `.tc-resizer` with an additional class such as `btc-rgrid-cell-resizer`. Keep the visible line simple and kill any old double-line `::after` grip decoration.

```css
.btc-rgrid-cell > .tc-resizer.btc-rgrid-cell-resizer {
  position: absolute;
  z-index: 30;
  top: calc(var(--btc-rgrid-cell-gap) / 2);
  right: calc(var(--btc-rgrid-handle-size) / -2);
  bottom: calc(var(--btc-rgrid-cell-gap) / 2);
  width: var(--btc-rgrid-handle-size);
  cursor: ew-resize;
  background: transparent;
  touch-action: none;
  user-select: none;
}

.btc-rgrid-cell > .tc-resizer.btc-rgrid-cell-resizer::before {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  top: 12%;
  bottom: 12%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%);
  width: 1px;
  border-radius: 999px;
  background: var(--btc-rgrid-handle-line);
  opacity: 0.38;
}

.btc-rgrid-cell > .tc-resizer.btc-rgrid-cell-resizer::after {
  content: none !important;
  display: none !important;
}
```

